  "prompt": "What determines the specific heat of a substance?",
  "response": "The specific heat of a substance is determined by the molecular structure and bonding within the substance. It is defined as the amount of heat energy required to raise the temperature of one unit of mass of the substance by one degree Celsius or Kelvin. \n\nAt the atomic level, the specific heat capacity of a substance depends on factors such as the number of atoms in its molecules, the strength of the bonds between the atoms, and the substance's ability to store heat energy in the form of vibrational and rotational energy. \n\nIn general, substances with strong bonds and high molecular weights tend to have higher specific heat capacities, as more energy is required to cause the molecules to vibrate and move, and thus increase their temperature. Additionally, the phase of the substance (solid, liquid, or gas) also influences its specific heat capacity, as the arrangement and movement of molecules differ in each phase.",
